<subSubSection id="6D837C85103BFF9ADBB2FB5048B82D46" lastPageId="32" lastPageNumber="133" pageId="30" pageNumber="131" type="description">
<paragraph id="25262F0E103BFFA4DBB2FB504D582F18" blockId="30.[151,535,1014,1077]" box="[151,365,1050,1077]" pageId="30" pageNumber="131">
(
<figureCitation id="BDA2338B103BFFA4DBBAFB504CC32F18" box="[159,246,1050,1077]" captionStart="FIGURES 23–28" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1360,1384]" captionTargetBox="[162,1425,181,1336]" captionTargetId="figure-29@6.[162,1425,181,1336]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 23–28. Asianthrips species. (23) A. setifer, female (mac); (24) A. sufflavus, female (mac); (25) A. sulawesiensis, female (mac). A. taiwanus, 26–27; (26) Female (mac); (27) Male (mic); (28) A. vietnamensis, female (mac)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404872" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404872/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="131">Figs 25</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="BDA2338B103BFFA4DA27FB504D502F18" box="[258,357,1051,1077]" captionStart="FIGURES 137–144" captionStartId="33.[151,264,1673,1697]" captionTargetBox="[165,1423,181,1649]" captionTargetId="figure-17@33.[165,1423,181,1649]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="FIGURES 137–144. Asianthrips sulawesiensis, sp. n., female (mac). (137) Head; (138) Antenna; (139) Metanotum; (140) Ferna–mesopresternum; (141) Fore wing; (142) Pelta; (143) Tergite IV; (144) Tube." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404928" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404928/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="131">137–144</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="25262F0E103BFFA4DBB2FB284E612D90" blockId="30.[151,1437,1122,2013]" pageId="30" pageNumber="131">
<emphasis id="17EDF31C103BFFA4DBB2FB284D432F51" box="[151,374,1123,1149]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="131">Female macroptera</emphasis>
. Body brown (
<figureCitation id="BDA2338B103BFFA4D900FB284E492F50" box="[549,636,1122,1149]" captionStart="FIGURES 23–28" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1360,1384]" captionTargetBox="[162,1425,181,1336]" captionTargetId="figure-29@6.[162,1425,181,1336]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 23–28. Asianthrips species. (23) A. setifer, female (mac); (24) A. sufflavus, female (mac); (25) A. sulawesiensis, female (mac). A. taiwanus, 26–27; (26) Female (mac); (27) Male (mic); (28) A. vietnamensis, female (mac)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404872" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404872/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="131">Fig. 25</figureCitation>
). Antennal segment III yellow; remaining segments uniformly brown, but segment IV very slightly yellowish at base. All femora brown, Fore femora yellowish at apical 1/3, mid and hind femora yellowish at apical 1/5–1/4; all tibiae and tarsi yellow. Fore wings and prominent body setae almost colourless. Head (
<figureCitation id="BDA2338B103BFFA4DA43FB844DFD2FC4" box="[358,456,1231,1257]" captionStart="FIGURES 137–144" captionStartId="33.[151,264,1673,1697]" captionTargetBox="[165,1423,181,1649]" captionTargetId="figure-17@33.[165,1423,181,1649]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="FIGURES 137–144. Asianthrips sulawesiensis, sp. n., female (mac). (137) Head; (138) Antenna; (139) Metanotum; (140) Ferna–mesopresternum; (141) Fore wing; (142) Pelta; (143) Tergite IV; (144) Tube." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404928" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404928/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="131">Fig. 137</figureCitation>
) a little longer than wide, 1.07 times as long as wide; dorsal surface sculptured with transverse reticulation, but the reticles very weak or almost smooth between eyes. Cheeks weakly incut behind eyes, weakly rounded, weakly narrowed to base. Postocular setae shorter than eyes. Postocellar setae weakly developed, shorter than a diameter of posterior ocellus. Eyes well developed, 0.41–0.42 times as long as head. Antennal segments VII and VIII somewhat broadly fused, but VIII not constricted basally, cone-shaped (
<figureCitation id="BDA2338B103BFFA4DFE2FA14491F2E54" box="[1223,1322,1375,1401]" captionStart="FIGURES 137–144" captionStartId="33.[151,264,1673,1697]" captionTargetBox="[165,1423,181,1649]" captionTargetId="figure-17@33.[165,1423,181,1649]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="FIGURES 137–144. Asianthrips sulawesiensis, sp. n., female (mac). (137) Head; (138) Antenna; (139) Metanotum; (140) Ferna–mesopresternum; (141) Fore wing; (142) Pelta; (143) Tergite IV; (144) Tube." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404928" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404928/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="131">Fig. 138</figureCitation>
); segment III with three sense cones. The right maxillary stylet almost reaching postocular setae, but the left one not reaching at least in 
<typeStatus id="FA2291AC103BFFA4DA2EFAEC4D452EEC" box="[267,368,1447,1473]" pageId="30" pageNumber="131">holotype</typeStatus>
, rather wide apart, wider than 1/3 of the head width apart at the basal collar of head. Pronotum 0.58 times as long as head and 1.93 times as wide as long; pa about 1/2 the median pronotal length. Metanotum (
<figureCitation id="BDA2338B103BFFA4DB85FAA44D352D24" box="[160,256,1519,1545]" captionStart="FIGURES 137–144" captionStartId="33.[151,264,1673,1697]" captionTargetBox="[165,1423,181,1649]" captionTargetId="figure-17@33.[165,1423,181,1649]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="FIGURES 137–144. Asianthrips sulawesiensis, sp. n., female (mac). (137) Head; (138) Antenna; (139) Metanotum; (140) Ferna–mesopresternum; (141) Fore wing; (142) Pelta; (143) Tergite IV; (144) Tube." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404928" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404928/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="131">Fig. 139</figureCitation>
) weakly polygonally reticulated, but the reticles very weak at anterior portion. Prospinasternum largely developed. Mesopresternum and mesoeusternum (
<figureCitation id="BDA2338B103BFFA4D9F0F9584F022D00" box="[725,823,1555,1581]" captionStart="FIGURES 137–144" captionStartId="33.[151,264,1673,1697]" captionTargetBox="[165,1423,181,1649]" captionTargetId="figure-17@33.[165,1423,181,1649]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="FIGURES 137–144. Asianthrips sulawesiensis, sp. n., female (mac). (137) Head; (138) Antenna; (139) Metanotum; (140) Ferna–mesopresternum; (141) Fore wing; (142) Pelta; (143) Tergite IV; (144) Tube." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404928" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404928/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="131">Fig. 140</figureCitation>
) narrowly fused medially, with long sutures between them at both sides; mesopresternum eroded medially. Fore tarsi unarmed. Fore wings with 5–6 duplicated cilia. Tergites not small (
<figureCitation id="BDA2338B103BFFA4DA54F9104DE62D58" box="[369,467,1627,1653]" captionStart="FIGURES 137–144" captionStartId="33.[151,264,1673,1697]" captionTargetBox="[165,1423,181,1649]" captionTargetId="figure-17@33.[165,1423,181,1649]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="FIGURES 137–144. Asianthrips sulawesiensis, sp. n., female (mac). (137) Head; (138) Antenna; (139) Metanotum; (140) Ferna–mesopresternum; (141) Fore wing; (142) Pelta; (143) Tergite IV; (144) Tube." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404928" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404928/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="131">Fig. 143</figureCitation>
), tergites III–V much wider than pronotum. S1 setae on tergite IX a little shorter than S2, about 0.7 times as long as tube, they are weakly expanded at apex. Tube (
<figureCitation id="BDA2338B103BFFA4D8D8F93448692DB4" box="[1021,1116,1663,1689]" captionStart="FIGURES 137–144" captionStartId="33.[151,264,1673,1697]" captionTargetBox="[165,1423,181,1649]" captionTargetId="figure-17@33.[165,1423,181,1649]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="FIGURES 137–144. Asianthrips sulawesiensis, sp. n., female (mac). (137) Head; (138) Antenna; (139) Metanotum; (140) Ferna–mesopresternum; (141) Fore wing; (142) Pelta; (143) Tergite IV; (144) Tube." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404928" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404928/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="131">Fig. 144</figureCitation>
) about 0.54 times as long as head. Anal setae almost as long as tube.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="25262F0E103BFFA4DBE2F98C49222C5C" blockId="30.[151,1437,1122,2013]" pageId="30" pageNumber="131">
<emphasis id="17EDF31C103BFFA4DBE2F98C4D432DCC" bold="true" box="[199,374,1735,1761]" pageId="30" pageNumber="131">Measurements</emphasis>
. Female 
<typeStatus id="FA2291AC103BFFA4DAC0F98C4E722DCC" box="[485,583,1735,1761]" pageId="30" pageNumber="131">holotype</typeStatus>
(mac.) in microns. Distended body length about 1800. Head length 172, width across cheeks 161. Compound eye dorsal length 70–73. Pronotum length 100, width 193. Fore wing length about about 690. Tube length 93, width across base 53. Antenna length 366, segments III–VIII length (width) as follows: 58 (28), 58 (28), 50 (25), 45 (22), 42 (20), 26 (12). Postocular setae about 50. Pronotal aa?, am?, ml?, pa about 50, epim about 60. S1 setae on tergite IX 65–67, S2 setae on tergite IX 70–72. Anal setae 90–92.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="25262F0E103BFFA4DBE2F83049402CF0" blockId="30.[151,1437,1122,2013]" pageId="30" pageNumber="131">
<emphasis id="17EDF31C103BFFA4DBE2F8304DA72CB9" box="[199,402,1915,1941]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="131">Male macroptera.</emphasis>
Colour and structure very similar to macropterous female, but smaller and slenderer. Head almost as long as wide. Fore tarsi unarmed. Fore wings with 5–5 duplicated cilia. Suture between mesopresternum and mesoeusternum nearly complete. S2 setae on tergite IX short and pointed. Tube 0.56 times as long as head.
</paragraph>
